04456nam a22006375i 9780292735019DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211977txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927350197 a10.7560/7071912doi  a(DE-B1597)588409  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aML3553b.C644 1977 7aSOC0110002bisacsh04a784.49731 aCoffin, Tristram Potter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe British Traditional Ballad in North America /cTristram Potter Coffin. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1977  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction to the Revised Edition -- tA Description of Variation in the Traditional Ballad of America -- tA Bibliographical Guide to Story Variation in the Traditional Ballad in America -- tThe Traditional Ballad as an Art Form -- tGeneral Bibliography of Titles Abbreviated in the Study of Story Variation -- tIndex to Ballads Discussed -- tA Supplement to The British Traditional Ballad in North America -- tPreface -- tA Note on Variation in the British Traditional Ballad in North America -- tA Bibliographical Guide to Story Variation in the British Traditional Ballad in North America -- tBibliography -- tDiscography -- tIndex to Standard Titles of Ballads and Songs0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTristram Potter Coffin’s The British Traditional Ballad in North America, published in 1950, became recognized as the standard reference to the published material on the Child ballad in North America. Centering on the theme of story variation, the book examines ballad variation in general, treats the development of the traditional ballad into an art form, and provides a bibliographical guide to story variation as well as a general bibliography of titles referred to in the guide. Roger deV. Renwick’s supplement to The British Traditional Ballad in North America provides a thorough review of all sources of North American ballad materials published from 1963, the date of the last revision of the original volume, to 1977. The references, which include published text fragments and published title lists of items in archival collections, are arranged according to each ballad’s story variations. Textual and thematic comparisons among ballads in the British and American tradition are made throughout. In his introductory essay Renwick synthesizes the various theoretical approaches to the phenomenon of variation that have appeared in scholarly publications since 1963 and provides examples from texts referred to in the bibliographical guide itself. The supplement, like its parent work, is an invaluable reference tool for the study of variation in ballad form, content, and style. Together with the reprinted text of the 1963 edition, the supplement provides an exhaustive bibliography to the literature on the British traditional ballad in North America.  afunded by Renwick  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBallads, EnglishzUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology.2bisacsh2 aRenwickefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70719140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292735019423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292735019/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK